com.topjohnwu.superuser.io

Class SuFile

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.io.File
      • com.topjohnwu.superuser.io.SuFile
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<File>

    public class SuFile
extends File
    A File implementation with root access.

    This class is meant to be used just like a normal File, so developers can access files via root shells without messing with command-lines. When a new SuFile is constructed, it will first check whether the target abstract path is accessible without root privileges. The checks are: whether the process have rw permission to the path, and whether the parent directory is writable so we can create/delete the target. If any of the checks doesn't pass, all operations will then be backed with root shell commands instead of the native implementations. If you want to bypass the check and always use the root shell for all methods, use SuFile(File, boolean) to construct the instance.

    If a root shell is required, it will get a Shell instance via Shell.getShell().

    The shell backed operations rely on the following shell tools: rm, rmdir, mv, ls, mkdir, and touch. These are all available on modern Android versions (tested on Lollipop+), earlier versions might need to install additional busybox to make things work properly.

      • setLastModified

        public boolean setLastModified(long time)
        Sets the last-modified time of the file or directory named by this abstract pathname.

        Note: On older Android devices, the touch commands accepts a different timestamp format than GNU touch. This shell implementation uses the format accepted in GNU coreutils, which is the same in more recent Android versions and busybox, so the operation might fail on older Android versions.

        Overrides:
        setLastModified in class File
        Parameters:
        time - The new last-modified time, measured in milliseconds since the epoch.
        Returns:
        true if and only if the operation succeeded; false otherwise.
